        <item>
            <guid isPermalink="true">http://w2sz.github.io/post/whaz-postcard/</guid>
            <title>WHAZ Postcard</title>
            <link>http://w2sz.github.io/post/whaz-postcard/</link>
            <category>history</category>
            <pubDate>Mon, 02 Jan 1933 04:28:23 +0800</pubDate>
            <description><![CDATA[ &lt;p&gt;From:   Kevin Roberts&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This postcard is in a scrapbook that I had in my attic from 1933. It was a reply postcard that WRPI’s predecessor (WHAZ) mailed to those who sent letters to the station&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note that RPI’s WHAZ-AM only broadcast on Monday evenings. But, once a month, it transmitted “clear channel” across the entire United  States.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The bell pictured has an interesting history, as it was used in the very first experiment demonstrating electrical communication in  1831. WHAZ used the bell in several broadcasts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I hope this is interesting, and that someone can use this image to post on WRPI’s website&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
 ]]></description>
        </item>
